* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 103-105.
* [Sorgenfrey plane](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sorgenfrey_plane) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Special Subsets of the Plane
spaces.description: See: Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 61-62.

spaces.name: Special Subsets of the Real Line
spaces.description: See: Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 61-62.

spaces.name: Stone-Cech Compactification of the Integers
spaces.description:
$\beta \mathbb{N}$ is the set of all ultrafilters on $\mathbb{N}$ (where we identify $n$ with the principal ultrafilter on $n$ so that $\mathbb{N} \subset \beta\mathbb{N}$). The topology on $\beta\mathbb{N}$ is generated by all sets of the form $\overline U = \{F \in \beta\mathbb{N}\ |\ U \in F\}$ for $U \subset \mathbb{N}$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 132-134.
* [The Stone–Čech compactification of the natural numbers](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stone%E2%80%93%C4%8Cech_compactification#The_Stone.E2.80.93.C4.8Cech_compactification_of_the_natural_numbers) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Stone-Cech Compactification
spaces.description:
The Stone-Čech compactification of a Tychonoff space $X$ is the unique compactification $\beta X$ with the property that any continuous $f: X \rightarrow Y$ into a compact Hausdorff space extends to a unique continuous $F: \beta X \rightarrow Y$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 129-132.
* [Stone–Čech compactification](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stone%E2%80%93%C4%8Cech_compactification) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Strong Parallel Line Topology
spaces.description:
Let $A$ be the subset of the plane $ \{ (x,0)\ |\ 0 < x \leq 1 \}$ and let $B$ be the subset $ \{ (x,1)\ |\ 0\leq x<1 \} $. Let $X = A \cup B$ as a set. The strong parallel line topology on $X$ is defined by taking as a basis all sets of the form $V = \{ (x,1)\ |\ a \leq x < b\}$ and $U = \{(x,0)\ |\ a < x \leq b \} \cup \{(x,1)\ |\ a<x<b\}$. 

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 114-115.

spaces.name: Strong Ultrafilter Topology
spaces.description:
Let $M$ be the set of all free ultrafilters on $\omega$. The Strong Ultrafilter Topology is the set $X = \omega \cup M$ with topology generated by points of $\omega$ along with all sets of the form $A \cup \{F\}$ for $A \in F \in M$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 135-136.

spaces.name: Tangora's Connected Space
spaces.description:
Let $X = \{\frac{m}{2^n}\} \subset \mathbb{Q}$ be the dyadic rationals, $Y = \mathbb{Q} \setminus X$ and $Z = \mathbb{P}$ the irrationals. Extend the usual topology on $\mathbb{R}$ by defining $X$ and $Y$ open along with sets of the form $\{z\} \cup \{w \in X \cup Y\ |\ |w-z|<\delta\}$ for $\delta > 0$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 150-151.

spaces.name: Telophase Topology
spaces.description:
Let $(X, \tau)$ be the topological space formed by adding to the ordinary closed unit interval $[0,1]$ another right end point, say $1^{\ast}$, with the sets $(a,1) \cup \{1^{*}\}$ as a local basis.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, p 92.

spaces.name: The Cantor Set
spaces.description:
$X = 2^\omega$ with the product topology.

Equivalently, $X$ may be defined geometrically using the 'middle-thirds' construction, so $X = [0,1]- \bigcup_{m=1}^\infty \bigcup_{k=0}^{3^{m-1}-1} \left(\frac{3k+1}{3^m},\frac{3k+2}{3^m}\right)$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 57-58.
* [Cantor set](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cantor_set) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: The Closed Infinite Broom
spaces.description:
For each $n \in \omega$ let $L_n$ be the line segment from $(0,0)$ to $(1,\frac{1}{n+1})$. The Infinite Broom is the set $\bigcup_{n \in \omega} L_n \cup \big((0,1] \times \{0\}\big) \subset \mathbb{R}^2$ with the subspace topology.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, p 139.
* [Infinite broom](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_broom) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: The compact interval $I:=[0,1]$
spaces.description: Consider the set $I:=\{t\in \mathbb R : 0\leq x \leq 1\}$ with the topology induced by $\mathbb R$.

spaces.name: The Extended Long Line
spaces.description:
The set of ordinals less than the least uncountable ordinal $\Omega$, with copies of the unit interval $[0,1]$ placed between each ordinal $\alpha$ and its successor $\alpha+1$, with the addition of $\Omega$, paired with the order topology.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 71-72.

spaces.name: The Infinite Broom
spaces.description:
For each $n \in \omega$ let $L_n$ be the line segment from $(0,0)$ to $(1,\frac{1}{n+1})$. The Infinite Broom is the set $\bigcup_{n \in \omega} L_n \cup \big((\frac{1}{2},1] \times \{0\}\big) \subset \mathbb{R}^2$ with the subspace topology.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, p 139.
* [Infinite broom](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_broom) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: The Infinite Cage
spaces.description:
For each $n \in \omega$, let $A_n = \{(\frac{1}{n}, y, 0) \in \mathbb{R}^3\ |\ y \geq 0\}$, $B_n = \{(0,y,0) \in \mathbb{R}^3\ |\ 2n - \frac{1}{2} \leq y \leq 2n + \frac{1}{2}\}$ and $C = \{(x,y,z) \in \mathbb{R}^3\ |\ 0 \leq x \leq \frac{1}{n}, y=2n, z=x(\frac{1}{n} -x)\}$. The Infinite Cage is the space $X = \bigcup_{n \geq 1} (A_n \cup B_n \cup C_n) \subset \mathbb{R}^3$ with the subspace topology.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, p 141.

spaces.name: The Integer Broom
spaces.description:
Let $X \subset \mathbb{R}^2$ with polar coordinates $\{(n,\theta)\ |\ n \in \omega, \theta \in \{0\} \cup \{1/n\}_{n=1}^\infty\}$. Define a topology on $X$ by taking as a basis all sets of the form $U \times V$ where is an open set in the right order topology on the non-negative integers and $V$ is open in $\{0\} \cup \{1/n\}_{n=1}^\infty \subset \mathbb{R}$. The only neighborhood of $(0,0)$ is $X$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, p 140.
* [The Integer broom topology](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_broom) on Wikipedia.

spaces.proof_of_topology:
In order to confirm the topology on the irrational numbers we simply must verify it is a subspace.  Let $\mathbb{I}$ be the set of irrational numbers.  Let $\tau$ denote the topology on $\mathbb{R}$.  
Observe both $\emptyset$ and $\mathbb{I}$ belong to $\tau_\mathbb{I}$ since
$$\emptyset = \mathbb{I} \cap \emptyset$$  $$\mathbb{I} = \mathbb{I} \cap \mathbb{R},$$
noting that both $\emptyset$ and $\mathbb{I}$ belong to $\tau$.

Taking the arbitrary union of any elements of $\tau_\mathbb{I}$ we note
$$ \bigcup_{i \in I} (\mathbb{I} \cap U_i) = \mathbb{I} \cap \bigcup_{i \in I} U_i $$
which is in $\tau_\mathbb{I}$ since $\bigcup_{i \in I} U_i \in \tau$.   
Taking the intersection of finitely-many elements of $\tau_\mathbb{I}$, we note 
$$ \bigcap_{i = 1}^n (\mathbb{I} \cap U_i) = \mathbb{I} \cap \bigcap_{i = 1}^n U_i $$
which is in $\tau_\mathbb{I}$ since $\bigcap_{i=1}^n U_i \in \tau$.
spaces.name: The Irrational Numbers
spaces.description:
Let $X$ be the complement of the rational numbers in $\mathbb{R}$ with the subspace topology.

Equivalently, $X \cong \omega^\omega$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 59-60.
* [Irrational number](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_number) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: The Long Line
spaces.description:
The lexicographic order topology on $\omega_1 \times [0,1)$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 71-72.
* [Long line](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_line_(topology)) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: The Open Long Line
spaces.description: Take the long line (The lexicographic order topology on $\omega_1 \times [0,1)$) and remove the smallest element.

spaces.name: The $p$-adic Topology on $\mathbb{Z}$
spaces.description:
Let $X$ consist of the set $\mathbb{Z}$ with topology generated by the basis of all sets of the form $U_m(n) = n + p^m \mathbb{Z}$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 81-82.
* [p-adic number](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-adic) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: The Post Office Metric
spaces.description:
If $d$ is the usual metric on $\mathbb{R}^2$, the post office metric $p$ is defined by: 
\[r(x,y) = \begin{cases}
    0 & x=y \\
    d(x,(0,0)) + d(y,(0,0)) & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\]

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, p 155.

spaces.name: The Radial Metric
The Rational Numbers
spaces.description:
Let $X = \mathbb{Q} = \{\frac{a}{b} : a,b \in \mathbb{Z}\}$ with the subspace topology.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 59-60.
* [Rational number](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Thomas' Corkscrew
spaces.description:
Take copies of [Thomas' plank](/brubeck/spaces/thomas-plank/) and use them to build a corkscrew as in the construction of the [Tychonoff corkscrew](/brubeck/spaces/tychonoff-corkscrew/).

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 113-114.

spaces.name: Thomas' Plank
spaces.description:
Let $L_0 = \{(x,0)\ |\ x \in (0,1)\}$ and for $i \geq 1$, $L_i = \{(x,\frac{1}{i}\ |\ x \in [0,1)\}$, and $X = \bigcup_{i=0}^\infty L_i$. If $i \geq 1$, each point of $L_i \setminus \{(0, \frac{1}{i})\}$ is open. Basis neighborhoods of $(0,\frac{1}{i})$ are subsets $L_i$ with finite complements. The sets $U_i(x,0) = \{(x,0)\} \cup \{(x,\frac{1}{n})\ |\ n > i\}$ form a basis for the points in $L_0$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 113-114.

spaces.name: Topologist's Sine Curve
spaces.description:
The Topologist's Sine Curve is the set $S = \{(x, \sin\frac{1}{x})\ |\ x \in (0,1]\} \cup \{(0,0)\}$ with the subspace topology inherited from $\mathbb{R}^2$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 137-138.
* [Topologist's sine curve](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topologist%27s_sine_curve) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Two Arrows Space
spaces.description: this is the same as the "weak parallel line topology"

spaces.name: Tychonoff Corkscrew
spaces.description:
For each ordinal $\alpha$ let $A_\alpha$ denote the linearly ordered set $-0, -1, -2, \dots, \alpha, \dots, 2, 1, 0)$ with the order topology. Let $P = A_{\omega_1} \times A_{\omega}$ and $P^* = P \setminus \{(\omega_1, \omega)\}$. We may regard $P^*$ as a rectangular lattice with coordinate axes $A_{\omega_1}$ and $A_\omega$. 

Form a corkscrew by taking a (countably) infinite stack of copies of $P^*$ by slitting each $P*$ immediately below the positive $A_{\omega_1}$ axis and the joining the fourth quadrant of one plane to the first quadrant of the one immediately below it. Complete the space by adjoining a point $a^+$ with neighborhoods all points above a certain level and $a^-$ with neighborhoods all points below a certain level.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 109-111.

spaces.name: Tychonoff Plank
spaces.description:
The Tychonoff Plank is the space $[0,\omega] \times [0,\omega_1]$ where each factor has the order topology.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 106-107.
* [Tychonoff plank](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tychonoff_plank) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Uncountable Discrete Ordinal Space
spaces.description:
$\{\alpha+1\ |\ \alpha < \Omega$ is a limit ordinal$\}$, paired with the order topology.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 70-71.

spaces.name: Uncountable Discrete Topology
spaces.description:
Let $X$ be an uncountable set and let all subsets of $X$ be open.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 41-42.
* [Discrete topology](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_topology) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Uncountable Excluded Point Topology
spaces.description:
The excluded point topology on a set $X$ consists of $X$ along with all subsets of $X$ which do not contain some fixed point $p$, $\tau = \{U \subset X : p \not\in U \} \cup \{X\}$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 47-48.
* [Excluded point topology](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Excluded_point_topology) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Uncountable Fort Space
spaces.description: DELETE ME

spaces.name: Uncountable Modified Fort Space
spaces.description:
Let $Y$ be uncountable, $a,b$ points outside of $Y$ and $X = Y \cup \{a,b\}$. Let $Y$ be discrete and let a set containing $a$ or $b$ be open if and only if it contains all but a finite number of points of $Y$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 55-56.
* [Fort space](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_space) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Uncountable Particular Point Topology
spaces.description:
Let $X$ be any uncountable set and fix a particular point $p$ of $X$. A set is open in this topology if it contains $p$ or is empty.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 44-46.
* [Particular point topology](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Particular_point_topology) on Wikipedia.

spaces.name: Uncountable Products of $\mathbb{Z}^+$
spaces.description:
The product topology on $(\mathbb{Z}^+)^\kappa$ where $\kappa$ is an uncountable cardinal. For definiteness, take $\kappa > 2^\mathfrak{c}$.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 123-124.

spaces.name: Unit Cirlce
spaces.description: $X:=\mathbb S^1 :=\{z\in\mathbb C : |z|=1\}\subseteq \mathbb C$

spaces.name: Unit sphere $\mathbb S^2$
spaces.description: $\mathbb S^2:=\{ x\in \mathbb R^3 : ||x||=1 \}\subseteq \mathbb R^3$ is the surface of the unit ball in Euclidean three-space

spaces.name: Weak Parallel Line Topology
spaces.description:
Let $A$ be the subset of the plane $ \{ (x,0)\ |\ 0 < x \leq 1 \}$ and let $B$ be the subset $ \{ (x,1)\ |\ 0\leq x<1 \} $. Let $X = A \cup B$ as a set. The weak parallel line topology on $X$ is defined by taking as a basis all sets of the form $W = \{(x,0)\ |\ a<x<b \} \cup \{ (x,1)\ |\ a \leq x < b\}$ and $U = \{(x,0)\ |\ a < x \leq b \} \cup \{(x,1)\ |\ a<x<b\}$. 
This space is also known as the "two arrows space". The weak parallel line topology is an order topology.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, pp 114-115.
* Engelking, R. (1989), General Topology, p. 212, Exercise 3.10.C

spaces.name: Wheel without Its Hub
spaces.description:
Let $X = \{(x,y) \in \mathbb{R}^2\ |\ 0< x^2 + y^2 \leq 1\}$ with topology generated by the standard Euclidean topology, along with all open intervals on the radii contained in the open unit disc.

See also:

* Steen, L. A.; Seebach, J. A. (1970), [Counterexamples in Topology](http://books.google.com/books/about/Counterexamples_in_Topology.html?id=DkEuGkOtSrUC), Dover, p 150.

properties.name: 2-Markov-Winning Menger
properties.description: The second player has a $2$-Markov winning strategy in the Menger game (relying on only the round number and two most recent moves of the opponent).

properties.name: Alexandrov
properties.description:
A topological space $X$ is called an _Alexandrov space_ (or a _finitely generated space_) if the family of open sets is closed under arbitrary intersections. Equivalently, $X$ is Alexandrov if any of the following properties hold.

* Each $x \in X$ has a unique smallest neighborhood.
* For each $A \subseteq X$, $A$ is open iff $A \cap Y$ is open in the subspace $Y$ for each finite $Y \subseteq X$.
* There is a quasi-order (_i.e._, a reflexive and transitive relation) $\preceq$ on $X$ such that for each $A \subseteq X$, $A$ is open iff for $\{ y \in X : y \preceq x \} \subseteq A$ for each $x \in X$.

_References:_

* Wikipedia's [Alexandrov topology](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandrov_topology) article.
* Topospace's [Alexandrov space](http://topospaces.subwiki.org/wiki/Alexandrov_space) article.

properties.name: Anti-Hausdorff
properties.description: A topological space is anti-Hausdorff if every pair of points $x \neq y$ cannot be distinguished by open neighborhoods, that is $U \cap V \neq \emptyset$ for all neighborhoods $U$ of $x$ and $V$ of $y$.

properties.name: Arc Connected
properties.description:
An arc in a space $X$ is an injective continuous map $f:[0,1] \rightarrow X$.

A space $X$ is arc connected if, given any two distinct $x,y \in X$ there is an arc $f$ with $f(0)=x$ and $f(1)=y$.

properties.name: Baire
properties.description: A space $X$ is Baire if the countable union of closed nowhere dense subsets of $X$ has empty interior.

properties.name: Banach-Mazur Winning: Player I, Stationary
properties.description: Player I has a stationary winning strategy in the [Banach-Mazur game](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banach%E2%80%93Mazur_game). (A stationary strategy is one that relies only on the opponent's most recent move).

properties.name: Banach-Mazur Winning: Player II, Stationary
properties.description: Player II has a stationary winning strategy in the [Banach-Mazur game](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banach%E2%80%93Mazur_game). (A stationary strategy is one that relies only on the opponent's most recent move).

properties.name: Biconnected
properties.description: A connected set $X$ is biconnected if it is not the union of two disjoint nondegenerate connected subsets.

properties.name: Cardinality < $\mathfrak(c)$
properties.description: A set $S$ has cardinality < $\mathfrak(c)$ if there is an injective function (not necessarily continuous) $f:S \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ but no such bijective function.

properties.name: Cardinality $\leq 2^{\mathfrak(c)}$
properties.description: A set $S$ has cardinality $\leq 2^{\mathfrak(c)}$ if there is an injective function (not necessarily continuous) $f:S \rightarrow P(\mathbb{R})$, where $P(\mathbb{R})$ is the set of subsets of $\mathbb{R}$.

properties.name: Cardinality $\mathfrak(c)$
properties.description: There is a bijection from $X$ to $2^\omega$.

properties.name: Closure preserves cardinalities
properties.description: $|cl(A)|=|A|$ for all $A\subseteq X$.

properties.name: Collectionwise Normal
properties.description:
A topological space $X$ is called '''collectionwise normal''' if for every discrete family $(F_i)_{i \in I}$  of closed subsets of $X$ there exists a pairwise disjoint family of open sets $U_{i \in I}$, such that $F_i \subseteq U_i$.
Here, a discrete family is a family of subsets such that each point of $X$ has a neighborhood meeting at most one of the subsets.

Source: 
http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Collectionwise_normal_space

properties.name: Compact
properties.description: A space $X$ is compact if every open cover of $X$ has a finite subcover.

properties.name: Completely Normal
properties.description:
A completely normal space is one for which any subspace is normal (under the subspace topology).

Equivalently, a space is completely normal provided any two separated sets can be placed into disjoint open sets.

(Two sets $A$ and $B$ are separated whenever $\operatorname{cl}(A) \cap B = A \cap \operatorname{cl}(B) = \emptyset$.)

properties.name: Completely Regular
properties.description:
A completely regular space is one in which points and closed sets can be separated by a function.

(In other words, a space is completely regular if, given a closed set $A$ and a point $b \notin A$, there is a continuous function $f:X \rightarrow [0,1]$ such that $f(A) = \{0\}$ and $f(b)=1$.)

properties.name: Connected
properties.description: A space $X$ is connected if given any two disjoint open $U, V \subset X$ with $U \cup V = X$, one of $U$ or $V$ must be empty.

properties.name: Corson compact
properties.description: Homeomorphic to a compact subspace of a $\Sigma$-product of real lines.

properties.name: Countable Chain Condition
properties.description: A space $X$ satisfies the countable chain condition (often abbreviated CCC) if every pairwise-disjoint collection of open subsets of $X$ is at most countable.

properties.name: Countable
properties.description:
A space $X$ is countable if there is an injective function (not necessarily continuous) $f:X \rightarrow \mathbb{N}$.

Note: countable is sometimes considered to imply not finite. "Countably infinite" should be used if this is not clear in context.

properties.name: Countably Compact
properties.description: A space $X$ is countably compact if every countable open cover of $X$ has a finite subcover.

properties.name: Countably Metacompact
properties.description: A space $X$ is countably metacompact if every countable open cover of $X$ has a point-finite open refinement which covers $X$.

properties.name: Countably Paracompact
properties.description: A space $X$ is countably paracompact if every countable open cover of $X$ has a locally finite open refinement which covers $X$.

properties.name: Countably Tight
properties.description: A topological space $X$ is countably tight, if for each $A\subseteq X$ and each $p\in \overline A$ there is a countable subset $D\subseteq A$ such that $p\in \overline D$.

properties.name: Cozero Complemented
properties.description: A $T_{3\frac{1}{2}}$ space is Cozero Complemented if for every cozero $U \subset X$ there is a cozero $V \subset X\setminus U$ such that $U \cup V$ is dense in $X$.

properties.name: Discrete
properties.description: A space is discrete if every point is isolated.

properties.name: Eberlein compact
properties.description: Embeddable as a compact subspace of $\Sigma^* R^\kappa=\{x\in R^\kappa: n<\omega\Rightarrow|\{\alpha<\kappa:x(\alpha)>\frac{1}{n}\}|<\omega\}$ for some $\kappa$.

properties.name: Extremally Disconnected
properties.description: A space is extremally disconnected if it is $T_2$ and the closure of every open set is open.

properties.name: Finite
properties.description: A topological space on a set $X$ is said to be finite provided the cardinality of $X$ is finite.

properties.name: First Countable
properties.description: A space $X$ is first countable if there is a countable local basis at every point of $X$.

properties.name: Fixed Point Property
properties.description:
A topological space $X$ has the fixed point property if every continuous selfmap has at least one fixed point.

See also:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fixed-point_property

properties.name: Fréchet Urysohn
properties.description: A topological space $X$ is called Fréchet Urysohn if for each $A\subseteq X$ and each $p\in \overline A$ there is a sequence in $A$ converging to $p$.

properties.name: Fully Normal
properties.description:
A cover $\{V_{\beta}\}$ of $X$ is a star refinement of another cover $\{U_{\alpha}\}$ of $X$ if for every $x \in X$ there is some $U_{\alpha}$ such that $\cup \{V_{\beta}\,|\,x \in V_{\beta}\} \subset U_{\alpha}$.

A space is fully normal if every open cover has an open star refinement.

properties.name: Fully $T_4$
properties.description: A space is fully $T_4$ if and only if it is $T_1$ and fully normal.

properties.name: Groupable
properties.description: A topological space is called groupable if it is homeomorphic to a topological group.

properties.name: Has Dispersion Point
properties.description: A connected set $X$ has a dispersion point $p$ if $X \setminus \{p\}$ is totally disconnected.

properties.name: Homogenous
properties.description: A space $X$ is homogenous if for each $a,b\in X$ there is a homeomorphism $\phi : X \to X$ such that $\phi(a)=b$. In other words: the group of homeomorphisms acts transitively.

properties.name: Hyperconnected
properties.description: A space is hyperconnected if it contains no disjoint open subsets.

properties.name: k-lindelof
properties.description:
A family $\mathcal U$    of open subsets of a topological space $X$ is called a $k$-cover if every compact subset of $X$ is contained in one of the members.

A space $X$ is $k$-Lindelöf if every open $k$-cover has a finite $k$-subcover.

properties.name: $k_\omega$
properties.description: A topological space is a $k_\omega$ space if there is an increasing sequence of compact Hausdorff subsets $K_1\subseteq K_2 \subseteq K_3 \subseteq \cdots$ such that the topology on $X$ is final with respect to the subsets $(K_n)_n$.

properties.name: KC
properties.description: A topological space is KC if every compact subset is closed.

properties.name: Lindelof
properties.description: A space $X$ is Lindelof if every open cover of $X$ has a countable subcover.

properties.name: Locally Arc Connected
properties.description: A space $X$ is locally connected if $X$ has a basis consisting of arc connected sets.

properties.name: Locally Compact
properties.description: A space $X$ is locally compact if each point of $X$ has a compact neighborhood.

properties.name: Locally Connected
properties.description: A space $X$ is locally connected if $X$ has a basis consisting of connected sets.

properties.name: Locally countable
properties.description: The space has a base of open sets with countable cardinality.

properties.name: Locally Hausdorff
properties.description: A space is locally Hausdorff if each point has a neighborhood which is Hausdorff.

properties.name: Locally metrizable
properties.description: A topological space is locally metrizable if each point $p$ has a neighborhood which is metrizable.

properties.name: Locally Path Connected
properties.description: A space $X$ is locally connected if $X$ has a basis consisting of path connected sets.

properties.name: Markov-Winning Menger
properties.description: The second player has a Markov winning strategy in the Menger game (relying on only the round number and most recent move of the opponent).

properties.name: Maximal Compact
properties.description: A compact topology is maximal compact if it is not contained in a strictly finer compact topology.

properties.name: Menger
properties.description: A space $X$ is **Menger** if for every sequence of covers $\langle \mathcal U_0, \mathcal U_1, \dots \rangle$ of the space $X$, there exists a sequence $\langle \mathcal F_0, \mathcal F_1, \dots \rangle$ such that $\mathcal F_n\subseteq \mathcal U_n$, $|\mathcal F_n|<\omega$, and $X\subseteq\bigcup_{n<\omega}\bigcup \mathcal F_n$.

properties.name: Metacompact
properties.description: A space $X$ is metacompact if every open cover of $X$ has a point-finite open refinement which covers $X$.

properties.name: Metrizable
properties.description:
A metric is a function $d:X \times X \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ such that for all $x,y,z \in X$
i) $d(x,y) \geq 0$ and $d(x,y)=0$ if and only if $x=y$
ii) $d(x,y) = d(y,x)$
iii) $d(x,z) \leq d(x,y) + d(y,z)$

Given a metric $d$ and $x \in X, \epsilon \in \mathbb{R}$, define $B(x,\epsilon) = \{y \in X\, |\, d(x,y)<\epsilon\}$. Then the set $\{B(x,\epsilon)\, |\, \epsilon \in \mathbb{R}\}$ is a basis for a topology, called the topology generated by $d$. A space $(X, \tau)$ is metrizable if there is some metric $d$ on $X$ which generates the topology $\tau$.

properties.name: Normal
properties.description:
A normal space is one in which disjoint closed sets can be separated by open neighborhoods.

(In other words, a space is normal if, given disjoint closed sets $A$ and $B$, there are disjoint open sets $O_A$ and $O_B$ containing $A$ and $B$, respectively.)

properties.name: Paracompact
properties.description: A space $X$ is paracompact if every open cover of $X$ has a locally finite open refinement which covers $X$.

properties.name: Path Connected
properties.description:
A path in a space $X$ is a continuous map $f:[0,1] \rightarrow X$.

A space $X$ is path connected if, given any two $x,y \in X$ there is a path $f$ with $f(0)=x$ and $f(1)=y$.

properties.name: Perfectly Normal
properties.description: A space $X$ is perfectly normal if, for any disjoint closed sets $A$ and $B$, there is a continuous function $f: X \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ such that $f^{-1}(\{0\}) = A$ and $f^{-1}(\{1\}) = B$.

properties.name: Proximal
properties.description:
The entourage-picker has a winning strategy in Bell's proximal game.

MR3239205: Bell, Jocelyn R., An infinite game with topological consequences. Topology Appl. 175 (2014), 1–14.

properties.name: Pseudocompact
properties.description: A space $X$ is pseudocompact if every continuous function $f:X \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is bounded.

properties.name: Regular
properties.description:
A regular space is one in which a closed set and a point not contained in it can be separated by open neighborhoods.

(In other words, a space is regular if, given a closed set $A$ and a point $b \notin A$, there are disjoint open sets $O_A$ and $O_b$ containing $A$ and $b$, respectively.)

properties.name: Rothberger
properties.description: A space $X$ is **Rothberger** if for every sequence of covers $\langle \mathcal U_0, \mathcal U_1, \dots \rangle$ of the space $X$, there exists a sequence $\langle U_0, U_1, \dots \rangle$ such that $U_n \in\mathcal U_n$ and $X\subseteq\bigcup_{n<\omega}U_n$.

properties.name: Scattered
properties.description:
A space is scattered if it contains no nonempy dense-in-itself subsets.

Equivalently, a space is scattered if every non-empty subspace $Y$ contains a point which is isolated in $Y$.

properties.name: Second Category
properties.description: A space $X$ is second category if it cannot be written as a countable union of nowhere-dense subsets of $X$.

properties.name: Second Countable
properties.description: A space is said to be second countable if it has a countable basis.

properties.name: Semiregular
properties.description: A space is semiregular if it has a basis $\mathcal{B}$ of open sets such that $\operatorname{int}(\operatorname{cl}(O)) = O$ for every $O \in \mathcal{B}$.

properties.name: Separable
properties.description: A space is separable if it has a countable dense subset.

properties.name: Sequential
properties.description: A topological space is sequential if every sequentially closed set is closed (equivalently, every sequentially open set ist open), no separation axioms are assumed.

properties.name: Sequentially Compact
properties.description: A space $X$ is sequentially compact if every sequence in $X$ has a convergent subsequence.

properties.name: $\sigma$-compact
properties.description: A space is $\sigma$-compact if it is the union of countably many compact subsets.

properties.name: $\sigma$-Locally Compact
properties.description: A space is $\sigma$-locally compact if and only if it is $\sigma$-compact and locally compact.

properties.name: $\sigma$-Locally Finite Base
properties.description: A collection of subsets is $\sigma$-locally finite if it is a countable union of locally finite subcollections.

properties.name: $\sigma$-relatively-compact
properties.description: $X=\bigcup_{n<\omega}R_n$, where $R_n$ is relatively compact to $X$, that is, for every cover of $X$, there exists a finite subcollection which covers $R_n$.

properties.name: Sober
properties.description:
A topological space $X$ is *sober* such that every irreducible closed subset of $X$ is the closure of exactly one point of $X$: that is, this closed subset has a unique generic point.

Alternatively, if it coincides with the topological space of points of it locale of opens.

[Wikipedia](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sober_space)

[nlab](http://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/sober+topological+space)

properties.name: Spectral space
properties.description:
A compact sober space for which the collection of compact open subsets is closed under finite intersections and forms a base for the topology. [wiki](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sober_space)

Hochster's theorem: such spaces are homeomorphic to the prime spectrum of a commutive ring.

properties.name: Strongly Connected
properties.description: A space $X$ is strongly connected if every continuous function $f:X \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is constant.

properties.name: Strongly KC
properties.description: A topological space is strongly KC if every countably compact subset is closed.

properties.name: Strongly Locally Compact
properties.description: A space $X$ is strongly locally compact if every point in $X$ has an open neighborhood with compact closure.

properties.name: $T_0$
properties.description: A space is $T_0$ (or Kolmogorov) if, given any two distinct points, there is an open set containing one but not the other.

properties.name: $T_1$
properties.description: A space is $T_1$ (or Fréchet) if, given any two distinct points, each has an open set not containing the other.

properties.name: $T_2$
properties.description: A space is $T_2$ (or Hausdorff) if, given any two distinct points $a$ and $b$, there are disjoint open sets $O_a$ and $O_b$ containing $a$ and $b$, respectively.

properties.name: $T_3$
properties.description: A $T_3$ (or regular Hausdorff) space is one that is both regular and $T_1$.

properties.name: $T_4$
properties.description: A $T_4$ (or normal Hausdorff) space is one that is both normal and $T_1$.

properties.name: $T_5$
properties.description: A $T_5$ (or completely normal Hausdorff) space is one that is both completely normal and $T_1$.

properties.name: $T_6$
properties.description: A $T_6$ (or perfectly normal Hausdorff) space is one that is both $T_1$ and perfectly normal.

properties.name: $T_{2 \frac{1}{2}}$
properties.description:
A $T_{2 \frac{1}{2}}$ space is one in which distinct points are separated by closed neighborhoods.

(In other words, a space is $T_{2 \frac{1}{2}}$ if, given any two distinct points $a$ and $b$, there are open sets $O_a$ and $O_b$ containing $a$ and $b$, respectively, such that $cl(O_a)$ and $cl(O_b)$ are disjoint.)

(Reminder: Add the synonym "Urysohn" once the outdated "Urysohn" has been removed from the database.)

properties.name: $T_{3 \frac{1}{2}}$
properties.description: A $T_{3 \frac{1}{2}}$ (or completely regular Hausdorff) space is one that is both completely regular and $T_1$.

properties.name: Topological Manifold
properties.description: a topological manifold is a topological space which is locally homeomorphic to (finite dimensional, possibly zero-dimensional) Euclidean space. We do not assume paracompact or Hausdorff here.

properties.name: Topologically Complete
properties.description:
A metric $d$ on a space $X$ is complete if every Cauchy sequence in $X$ converges.

A space $(X,\tau)$ is topologically complete if $\tau$ can be generated by a complete metric.

properties.name: Totally Disconnected
properties.description: A space is totally disconnected if the only components are single points.

properties.name: Totally Path Disconnected
properties.description: A space $X$ is totally path disconnected if the only paths in $X$ are constant.

properties.name: Totally Separated
properties.description: A space $X$ is totally separated if, given any two distinct $x,y \in X$ there are disjoint open $U, V \subset X$ containing $x$ and $y$ respectively with $X = U \cup V$.

properties.name: Ultraconnected
properties.description: A space is ultraconnected if it contains no disjoint closed subsets.

properties.name: Urysohn
properties.description: A space $X$ is Urysohn if, given any two distinct $a,b \in X$ there is a continuous function $f:X \rightarrow [0,1]$ such that $f(a) = 0$ and $f(b)=1$.

properties.name: US
properties.description: A topological space is US (or sequentially Hausdorff) if it has unique sequential limits.

properties.name: Weakly Countably Compact
properties.description: A space $X$ is weakly countably compact if every infinite subset of $X$ has a limit point.

properties.name: Weakly Lindelof
properties.description: A space $X$ is weakly Lindelof if every open cover of $X$ has a countable subcollection whose union is dense in $X$.

properties.name: Winning Menger
properties.description: The second player has a winning strategy in the Menger game.

properties.name: Zero Dimensional
properties.description: A space is zero dimensional if it has a basis of clopen sets.

properties.name: Čech complete
properties.description:
A space $X$ is Čech complete if it is $T_{3 \frac{1}{2}}$ and is a $G_\delta$ subset of some compactification of $X$.

Alternatively, $X$ is Čech complete iff there is a sequence $\mathcal{U}_0, \mathcal{U}_1, \mathcal{U}_2, \dots$ of open covers of $X$ such that whenever $\mathcal{F}$ is a filter of closed sets such that for each $n$ there is some $F_n \in \mathcal{F}$ with $F_n \subset U$ for some $U \in \mathcal{U}_n$, then $\cap F \neq \emptyset$.
